<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="40" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,1317,1983]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1717,1743]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Apart from its distinctive skull, with a rhombic postparietal bone and paired parietals (
<figureCitation box="[1346,1431,1717,1743]" captionStart="PLATE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,238,1626,1650]" captionTargetBox="[307,1289,197,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-257@11.[263,1331,162,1634]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="PLATE 4. Figure 1. Dorsal views of the skulls of Leptotyphlops. A. Leptotyphlops nigricans (MCZ 21473) and B. Leptotyphlops kafubi (FMNH 56374), both after List (1966). KEY to bone abbreviations from List, 1966: Ax = axis, At = atlas, Eo = exoccipital, F = frontal, M = maxilla, N = nasal, P = parietal, Pf = prefrontal, Po = prootic, So = supraoccipital. C. Leptotyphlops cairi, after Abdeen et al. (1991). KEY to bone abbreviations from Abdeen et al., 1991: B.OC. = basioccipital; B.SP. = basisphenoid; C.T.C. = cartilaginouis trebacula cranii; EX.OC. = exoccipital; FR. = frontal; L.P.P.MX. = lateral process of maxilla; MX. = maxilla; NA. = nasal; OC.CO. = occipital condyle; P.MX. = premaxilla; P.OT. = prootic; P.VO. = prevomer; PA. = palatine; PR. = parietal; PR.FR. = prefrontal; PR.L.DG. = lateral downgrowth of parietal; PT. = pterygoid; S.OC. = supraoccipital. The lines represent 1 mm to scale. The stipple indicates thin transparent membrane. Figure 2. Dorsal views of the skulls of Leptotyphlops. A. Leptotyphlops nigroterminus sp. nov. (ZMB 51610); B. Leptotyphlops macrurus (BMNH 1957.1.10.26); C. Leptotyphlops boulengeri (MCZ 40087); D. Leptotyphlops reticulatus (BMNH 1954.1.12.77). E. Leptotyphlops longicaudus (NMZB-UM 29371); F. Leptotyphlops blanfordii (BMNH 1977.833); G. Leptotyphlops nursii (FMNH 66158). H. Leptotyphlops scutifrons merkeri (NMZB 8089). The lines represent 1 mm to scale. KEY: f = frontal; n = nasal; p = parietal; pp = postparietal; so = supraoccipital." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6789072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6789072/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Plate 4</figureCitation>
, Fig. 2A), this unique form differs from all other African species in its light brown colouration with the distal portion of the tail black.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="40" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,1317,1983]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,1837,1863]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the diagnostic black tail tip; from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[1277,1339,1837,1862]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">niger</emphasis>
= black and 
<emphasis box="[200,303,1877,1902]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">terminus</emphasis>
= tip.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,1317,1983]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,810,1917,1943]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
Description (
<typeStatus box="[359,473,1917,1943]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">paratype</typeStatus>
variations in parentheses).
</emphasis>
Body cylindrical, with head and neck broadened and flattened, the short tail tapers slightly to a small terminal spine.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6789102" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6789102" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6789102/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" startId="40.[151,238,1801,1825]" targetBox="[276,1332,178,1785]" targetPageId="40">
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1437,1801,2033]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,388,1801,1825]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">PLATE 12. Figure 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Published, 2007" authorityName="Published" authorityYear="2007" box="[396,704,1802,1825]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigroterminus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[396,704,1802,1825]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Leptotyphlops nigroterminus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[712,798,1801,1825]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[712,798,1801,1825]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Dorsal and lateral views of the head of the holotype, MCZ 54813 
<emphasis box="[225,249,1837,1860]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">—</emphasis>
Karema, Tanzania. The line represents 1 mm to scale. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[848,951,1836,1860]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Figure 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sternfeld" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[959,1222,1837,1860]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="latirostris">
<emphasis box="[959,1222,1837,1860]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Leptotyphlops latirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Dorsal, lateral and ventral views of the head of MCZ 53261/57459 from Uvira, DDC. Drawings by J. Boundy. The line represents 1 mm to scale. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[220,324,1905,1929]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Figure 3.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[334,698,1906,1929]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName box="[334,694,1906,1929]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="scutifrons" subSpecies="merkeri">Leptotyphlops scutifrons merkeri</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Dorsal, lateral and ventral views of the head of the syntype, MCZ 31627 
<emphasis box="[226,250,1941,1964]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">—</emphasis>
Moshi, Tanzania. Drawings by J. Boundy. The line represents 1 mm to scale. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1109,1213,1940,1964]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Figure 4.</emphasis>
Dorsal views of the heads of: A. 
<emphasis box="[287,557,1975,1998]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sternfeld" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[287,553,1975,1998]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="latirostris">Leptotyphlops latirostris</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
MRAC 18014 (Uvira, Kivu), compared with B. 
<emphasis box="[1079,1437,1975,1998]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Published" authorityYear="2007" box="[1079,1433,1975,1998]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="scutifrons" subSpecies="pitmani">Leptotyphlops scutifrons pitmani</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
MRAC 18006 (Rwankuba, Rwanda), after 
<bibRefCitation author="Laurent" box="[610,774,2010,2033]" firstAuthor="Laurent" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" pagination="1 - 390" refId="ref59963" refString="Laurent, R. F. (1956) Contribution a l'Herpetologie de la region des Grands Lacs de l'Afrique Centrale. I: Generalites, II. Cheloniens, III. Ophidiens. Annales du Musee Royal du Congo Belge (Tervuren), (8 vo - Sciences Zoologiques), 48, 1 - 390, Pls. 1 - 31." type="journal article" year="1956">Laurent (1956)</bibRefCitation>
. The lines represent 1 mm to scale.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,152,978]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Snout rounded, rostral broad (0.53–0.67 head width, mean = 0.59), fused with the frontal, unguiform, extending well beyond the level of the eyes, a preoral groove present ventrally. Behind rostral, upper lip bordered by infranasal (nostril midway between rostral and supralabial along nasal suture), small anterior supralabial with width along lip twice that of infranasal, large but narrow ocular, and tall posterior supralabial. Supraoculars pentagonal, anteriorly wedged in between supranasal and ocular, posteriorly in straight contact with the hexagonal postfrontal, which is subequal in size to the supraoculars, interparietal and interoccipital. Parietals oblique and in contact with the posterior supralabials. Occipitals not fused (fused in all 
<specimenCount box="[1284,1424,392,418]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="generic" typeStatus="paratypes">5 paratypes</specimenCount>
). Temporal single. No mental, four infralabials.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,152,978]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Body covered with 14 rows of smooth, imbricate, subequal scales. Reduction to 12 rows on the tail takes place lateral to the subtriangular cloacal shield, which is entire (tail rows 
<quantity box="[1040,1101,512,538]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="in" value="12.0">12 in</quantity>
the 
<typeStatus box="[1158,1255,512,538]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">allotype</typeStatus>
, 
<quantity box="[1269,1332,512,538]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="in" value="10.0">10 in</quantity>
the 
<specimenCount pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="generic" typeStatus="paratypes">four paratypes</specimenCount>
). Total middorsals 236 (
<quantity box="[556,634,552,578]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.7912" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="in" value="228.0">228 in</quantity>
other male, 
<quantity box="[785,919,552,578]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.112" metricValueMax="7.62" metricValueMin="6.603999999999999" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="in" value="280.0" valueMax="300.0" valueMin="260.0">260–300 in</quantity>
females); subcaudals 23 (
<quantity box="[1230,1293,552,578]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.858" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="in" value="27.0">27 in</quantity>
other male; 
<quantity box="[151,254,592,618]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.604" metricValueMax="6.858" metricValueMin="6.35" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="in" value="26.0" valueMax="27.0" valueMin="25.0">25–27 in</quantity>
females).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,152,978]" box="[198,911,632,658]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Total length 
<quantity box="[346,446,632,658]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.59" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="159.0">159 mm</quantity>
, tail 
<quantity box="[502,588,632,658]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="12.0">12 mm</quantity>
; midbody diameter 
<quantity box="[821,907,632,658]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,152,978]" box="[198,1111,672,698]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Total length/diameter ratio 45 (46–84); total length/tail ratio 13.2 (11.7–14.8).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,152,978]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Middorsal seven scale rows medium brown, rostral and dorsal tail blackish-brown, paler brown ventrally, distal half of tail with black ring (in the smallest specimen of 
<quantity box="[886,970,752,778]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.2" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="82.0">82 mm</quantity>
total length only the extreme tip of the tail is black, in the other 
<typeStatus box="[441,553,792,818]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">paratypes</typeStatus>
the distal third of tail has black ring).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,152,978]" box="[198,1157,831,858]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,256,831,857]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Size.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation accessionNumber="MCZ 52634" box="[263,1153,832,858]" collectionCode="MCZ" country="Tanzania" location="Manyoni" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" specimenCount="1">
Largest specimen (
<accessionNumber box="[484,629,832,858]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/MCZ52634" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<collectionCode box="[484,549,832,858]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" name="Museum of Comparative Zoology" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="Museum">MCZ</collectionCode>
52634
</accessionNumber>
— 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:A77887C2FFFAFFD3FF02846745D4B4E7:2A0E600FFFF4FFD3FD34830D424CB46F" box="[673,782,832,858]" country="Tanzania" name="Manyoni" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Manyoni</location>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[794,901,832,858]" name="Tanzania" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
) 180 + 13 = 
<quantity box="[1052,1153,832,858]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.93" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="193.0">193 mm</quantity>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,152,978]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,302,871,897]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Habitat.</emphasis>
The habitat in western 
<collectingCountry box="[580,685,872,898]" name="Tanzania" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
is miombo woodland, but in the Masai 
<collectingRegion box="[1157,1219,872,898]" country="Tanzania" name="Mara" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Mara</collectingRegion>
Reserve in 
<collectingCountry box="[1359,1435,872,898]" name="Kenya" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Kenya</collectingCountry>
the vegetation is a mosaic of evergreen bushland and secondary 
<taxonomicName box="[904,985,912,937]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[904,985,912,937]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Acacia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
wooded grassland (White, 1983).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[198,1174,951,978]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,152,978]" box="[198,1174,951,978]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,359,951,977]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Distribution.</emphasis>
Southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[532,608,952,978]" name="Kenya" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Kenya</collectingCountry>
and western 
<collectingCountry box="[764,872,952,978]" name="Tanzania" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
, 
<quantity box="[884,1046,952,978]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="m" value="1300.0" valueMax="1600.0" valueMin="1000.0">1000–1600 m</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[1061,1160,952,978]" captionStart="PLATE 11" captionStartId="38.[151,238,1432,1456]" captionTargetBox="[415,1166,479,1405]" captionTargetId="figure-300@38.[415,1171,474,1408]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="PLATE 11. Leptotyphlops. Distribution of the Leptotyphlops scutifrons species group in East Africa. Type localities are labelled." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6789098" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6789098/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Plate 11</figureCitation>
